I've paused all scheduled tweets from this account.

There are more important things to talk about right now than R.

And there are people more qualified than I am to do the talking.

Let's listen to them.

#BlackLivesMatter
@lddurbin Thanks for signing up! It took longer than I had hoped but I'm really glad to have it out there now.

@bma310 @matandofelipes This course builds on my Fundamentals of R course (https://t.co/elrtt4SLh2). So, if you're totally new to R start with Fundamentals. If you've used R but want to improve your skills, check out Going Deeper with R.
@bma310 @matandofelipes There is nothing specific to R 4.0 if that's what you're asking. I do explore the new slice_max() from dplyr 1.0.

Educating ourselves about our past can, I perhaps naively hope, help move us toward a better future.

And I want to play my small part in helping us get there.

I'm starting by supporting the work of @eji_org.

The Equal Justice Initiative takes a historical perspective, showing that police violence against African Americans today is deeply tied to our history of slavery, lynching, and segregation.

https://t.co/UQ1CaNtmbV

I'm excited to launch this course, though it comes at a time when many are raising their voices about deep inequities.

Starting today, I'm donating 1% of sales of online courses to support organizations doing important work.

https://t.co/eP9G1BKWtZ
@matandofelipes Yes that's right. It's around 50 self paced video lessons and exercises complete with code and video walkthrough of solutions.

column3: Women in Statistics and Data Science
column18:
RT @WomenInStat: Just a shoutout to all you people out there learning #rstats, it's okay if you don't know everything by heart.

Googling i‚Ä¶

This analysis was done in #rstats. Code here:

https://t.co/Qn8TXh890z https://t.co/FphwxyoRL5

RT @mjfrigaard: Thank you!

Be sure to check out the rest of the #rstats tutorials on Storybench's 'Data Journalism in R'

https://t.co/O‚Ä¶
Great #rstats tutorial! https://t.co/pgBxFQihQ6
A good lesson for us all! https://t.co/na8f14vUvd

Once you've developed code to make your plot look nice, make it into a function!

Doing this, you can reuse your function throughout a project to give all of your plots a consistent look and feel.

https://t.co/tR0JpYQPMR

One final way to use text to explain findings: use annotations.

Annotations can help explain parts of the graph that may confuse your reader. https://t.co/5UbYSq9bij

And go a step further still by adding color to your titles using the new and amazing {ggtext} package.

https://t.co/jfd95GwEEm
Go a step further and add a title that focuses the reader's attention on this main finding. https://t.co/7L7PNqpNAK

Don't make the reader hunt for your main finding!

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               Add labels to your plot to EXPLAIN what's going on. https://t.co/1F0kX8F98U

The default ggplot look is a not great (hello, gray background).

Learn to declutter using the theme() function. Or, better yet, use theme_ipsum() from the {hrbrthemes} package.

https://t.co/NlOC0VWbW7 https://t.co/q6UwqaC93U

The data viz section of the course teaches you how to use color to highlight important findings.

Using a single color to bring out an important finding can help your reader make sense of your chart. https://t.co/N8zXfRlNvs

Concrete examples are a great way to explain abstract concepts.

So I used this now very well-known chart @jburnmurdoch throughout the data viz section to show each of these best practices. https://t.co/zsOUQJzs5B

I structured the data viz section around several best practices in data viz:

1. HIGHLIGHT important findings.
2. DECLUTTER visualizations to bring out main points.
3. EXPLAIN findings with text.
4. Customize your visualizations to make them SPARKLE. https://t.co/uA49LN5UYj

When you're learning about merging data, the best place for visual learners to go is the {tidyexplain} package by @grrrck.

With animations like this, it makes it easy to make sense of the various joins in dplyr.

This lesson from @kellybodwin will also help you write better functions.

https://t.co/p57xdzKht5

Stat545 also has a nice section on creating functions.

https://t.co/o2mvOR8Xv2

Want to go deeper on making your own functions? Check out Chapter 19 of R for Data Science.

https://t.co/HcIUq0203l

Learning to write your own functions can improve your efficiency. I wrote a blog post last year to help folks get started.

https://t.co/vbSsptcdtK

When you do anything with group_by() you can't forget to ungroup() afterwards.

Handy picture from @allison_horst to help us all remember!

I pretty much only ever use case_when(). For some reason, it just works better for my mind than anything else.

Apparently, I'm not alone, as this post from @mattdray shows.

https://t.co/PxOnHvyPuF

If you prefer video, @sharon000 has a nice video overview of case_when()

https://t.co/HhbkaitUrL

https://t.co/73dYDbkDse

Learning to use the newish pivot_longer() and pivot_longer() functions to reshape your data? Check out the pivoting vignette.

https://t.co/T96heWcUWa

https://t.co/V3U6yYIlNU

Getting text to fit in your #rstats plots can be challenging! Enter the {ggfittext} package.

üîó https://t.co/m6VkVMEKbi https://t.co/p4xCvR8Env

The stop and frisk program that the New York Police Department ran for years disproportionately impacted people of color. @peterpcarroll analyzed this data using #rstats and created an animated visualization that shows what he found.

https://t.co/Hox73VGI65
RT @hadleywickham: Are you black, indigenous, or a person of colour? If so, I'm holding open office hours this Friday: https://t.co/ESqnkdJ‚Ä¶

When @lauren_marietta looked at the Boston Police budget, she found some surprising things.

Learn more and read about other examples of #rstats being used to look at race and policing.

https://t.co/Hox73VGI65

Once you've cleaned and tidied your data, save it!

Use write_csv() to, um, write a CSV. https://t.co/6rvdIVPtna

write_rds() saves your data frame as an RDS file, R's data file format. https://t.co/aoqpv5LP57

Need to rename one variable? Use rename(). https://t.co/yGmgW4lEl9

Need to rename all of your variables? Check out set_names(). https://t.co/vNANvaPI8E

Need to merge two data frames? Check out the join functions from {dplyr}.

https://t.co/zsGzK3tw6N

Have two data frames and need to bind them together? Check out bind_rows()!

https://t.co/fKc2RuyIzV

Need to get proportions? Use group_by() and mutate() to do this!

https://t.co/EKR6rcHpDV

Need to create variables based on multiple conditions? case_when() is your friend!

https://t.co/PxOnHvheD7

Need to change your variable types? There is a whole set of functions for you: as.character(), as.numeric(), etc. Use them in a mutate() as such:

mutate(actually_numeric_variable = as.numeric(numeric_variable_masquerading_as_a_string))

If you have the opposite (NA's that should be values), check out replace_na().

https://t.co/2mK7BoozgE

Oftentimes, you have data where values should be missing (e.g. 999). You can use the na_if() function to convert them to NA.

https://t.co/0dtvWBHxUC

You often need to reshape your data. The pivot_longer() function is really helpful here.

https://t.co/T96heVVk4C

Once you have your data imported, the first step is to tidy it. Learn about the principles of tidy data in this article.

https://t.co/V3U6yYZXcu

Also check out the {rio} package. Just use its import() function and it will import any type of data.

https://t.co/ly9ntbEtxK

Got SPSS, SAS, or Stata files? Check out the {haven} package to import them to R.

https://t.co/YvnZT4t7XO

Excel. It's ubiqituous. Learn how to import data using the read_excel function from the {readxl} package.

https://t.co/OegLAC6Kuu

One of the cool things about R is you can download data directly from R using the download.file() function.

https://t.co/TyBqgpReRB
